"CORE_NARRATIVE: Traditional light field depth estimation fails in real-world scenarios because non-Lambertian reflections break the fundamental linear assumption of Epipolar Plane Images (EPIs). To resolve this, we physically decouple angular signals into ambient, parallax, and material components, using a dual-mask mechanism to adaptively route features based on surface reflectance. This paradigm shift from ignoring to explicitly modeling complex reflections enables robust, unified depth estimation across diverse multi-domain scenes.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with a stark contrast between the idealized linear EPI assumption in current literature and the chaotic, reflection-rich reality of practical robotics and 3D reconstruction tasks. Highlight that failing to handle non-Lambertian surfaces is not a minor edge case, but a fundamental roadblock that renders current depth estimation unreliable for real-world deployment.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by pointing out that existing methods either treat non-Lambertian regions as noise to be filtered or rely on computationally heavy high-resolution angular spectra that fail at practical low angular resolutions (e.g., 9x9). Conclude that a physically grounded, low-resolution geometric decomposition is strictly necessary to separate material residuals from true parallax before depth estimation begins.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the three-layer physical decomposition and Random Forest classifier as the exact mechanisms needed to extract geometric angular features (like angular gradients) that isolate material residuals without relying on high-res spectra. Explain that the GeometricDualMask architecture and domain-balanced sampling directly operationalize this physical prior, ensuring the network applies tailored feature routing rather than a flawed, one-size-fits-all linear assumption.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Structure the experiments to first prove the physical decoupling works (showcasing the 89.6% RF classification accuracy and 0.983 Cohen's d for angular gradients), and then demonstrate that the dual-mask routing eliminates depth artifacts on specular surfaces. Finally, validate the multi-domain generalization by showing that domain-balanced sampling prevents performance collapse in complex, mixed urban scenes compared to single-domain baselines.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that explicitly modeling and routing non-Lambertian reflections, rather than treating them as EPI anomalies, is the key to unlocking reliable light field depth estimation for real-world applications. End by framing the physical signal decoupling and dual-mask paradigm as a foundational step toward truly robust 3D perception in reflection-rich environments."